references: Table 1 report the results of our experiments. In general, our FedDAR achieved the best performance compared with the baselines.

Ablation Studies. i) re-weighting (RW): First two rows in Table 2 shows adding sample re-weighting can significantly improve the fairness across the domains. The minimum AUC among domains is improved by a large margin (>0.05absent0.05>0.05); ii) multi-head (MH),  domain as input feautre (DI) and  alternating update (Alter): Comparing three blocks in Table 2, we can see that adding multi-head itself cannot bring any improvement. We conjecture that alternating update prevents the overfitting of the heads with limited samples .This can also be reflected by the result in Table 1, where FedAvg+MH tends to perform badly on certain underrepresented domain especially when domain distributions are highly heterogeneous (α𝛼\alpha is small).  Meanwhile, using domain labels directly as feature input is not as good as multi-head, and not compatible with alternating update; iii) projection (Proj) and aggregation method (AGG): Results in Table 2 shows that using second-order aggregation with the projection of the features gives the best result.

We also conduct experiments for gender classification on FairFace with the same settings. The best representation dimension is k=2𝑘2k=2 for this task, probably due to the smaller diversity across the domains. We can see that the results shown in Table 4 have similar trend with the results in Table 1.

Average Performance Across Domains and Clients. Table 3 shows the average of AUCs across domains and clients. We can see that our methods, both FedDAR-WA and FedDAR-SA, achieve significantly better performance than all the baselines under both domain-wise and client-wise metrics. The gap between our domain-wise personalized approach and other client-wise personalized baselines shows the validity of learning domain-wise personalized model facing the diversity across domains. The reason that fine-tuning methods
induce worse result is mainly because of the imbalanced label distribution. Each local training dataset doesn’t have enough positive cases to do proper fine-tuning.

Fairness Across Domains. The AUCs of each specific domain in Table 3, show that our proposed FedDAR  method uniformly increases the AUC for each domain. The column of the minimum AUC among domains also verifies that our method indeed improve the fairness across the domains.

references: We perform additional experiments on digits dataset with five data domains with feature shift [33]. Details are described in the following paragraphs. From Table 5, we can see that FedDAR-WA outperform FedAvg consistently except the case where domain distributions are extremely heterogeneous (α=0.1𝛼0.1\alpha=0.1). In this case, each client tends to have data from only one domain. It is difficult for the proposed method to learn a good domain-specific head for the domain with the most different data (more obvious feature shift) under this circumstance. For other levels of heterogeneity, although the min and max domain accuracies are similar between FedAvg and FedDAR-WA, the average accuracies are improved as a result of domain-wise personalized model. One the other hand, without alternative update of the head and representation, FedAvg + Multi-head will overfit quickly. We don’t include the results of FedDAR-SA here because using representation dimension k≥64𝑘64k\geq 64 causes numerical instability during head aggregation and failure to converge. While using representation dimension k≤32𝑘32k\leq 32 leads to lower accuracy.
